-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">i)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Revised provisions - ‘Transforming Legal Aid: Next Steps’</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ii)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Legality of the residence test</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">iii)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The residence test- not fit for purpose</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 54pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">iv)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">iv)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The impact of the Residence test on the Law</span></p></td></tr><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:403.2pt"><ol start="5" type="A" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.06pt; padding-left:3.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The proposal that judicial reviews against public    </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">bodies should only be paid for if the Court grants permission for the application</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> to proceed</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">i)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">E</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">xisting measures and mechanisms that exist in the current legal aid and judicial system </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ii)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Failure of the Government to accurately evidence and/or quantify their justification </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 72pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">iii)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The impact that this proposal will have on day to day practice and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the long term effect on legal service provision</span></p></td></tr><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:403.2pt"><ol start="6" type="A" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 31.71pt; padding-left:4.29pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The proposal that legal aid should</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> be removed for all  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">cases assessed as having “borderline” prospects of success</span></li></ol></td></tr><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:403.2pt"><ol start="7" type="A" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 33.85pt; padding-left:2.15pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The proposed restriction on the scope of legal aid available to prisoners</span></li></ol></td></tr><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:403.2pt"><ol start="8" type="A" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 33.78pt; padding-left:2.22pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Conclusion </span></li></ol></td></tr><tr><td style="border-bottom-color:#000000; border-bottom-style:solid; border-bottom-width:0.5pt; border-left-color:#000000; border-left-style:solid; border-left-width:0.5pt; border-right-color:#000000; border-right-style:solid; border-right-width:0.5pt; border-top-color:#000000; border-top-style:solid; border-top-width:0.5pt; padding-left:5.4pt; padding-right:5.4pt; vertical-align:top; width:403.2pt"><ol start="9" type="A" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 29.4pt; padding-left:6.6pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Anne</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">xes</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">) Statement from the Local Authority perspective (NRPF; ADCS &amp; LGA)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ii) Shadow Equality Impact assessment </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">iii ) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Shadow </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">financial impact assessment</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">iv) Letter from the LSC Newsletter 20 June 2005</span></p></td></tr></table><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 18pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; text-indent:-18pt; widows:0"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">A.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Background to the proposals and the coming into </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">force of the Legal Aid, Sentencing and Punishment of Offenders Act, 2012 (LASPO)</span></p><h1 style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">9.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">The Committee will be aware that the Ministry of Justice’s (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">MoJ</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal"> consultation document </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">‘Transforming Legal Aid: Delivering a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">M</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">ore </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">C</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">redible and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">E</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">fficient </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">S</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:normal">ystem’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">(“new proposals”) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">was published </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">only</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal"> one week after the coming into force of the Legal Aid, Sentencing and Punishment of Offenders Act, 2012 (LASPO). </span></h1><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">LASPO constituted the most significant reform of the legal aid system in England &amp; Wales since the Access</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to Justice Act 1999, introducing sweeping cuts and removing whole categories of civil law from legal aid. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">As a result,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> many members of society, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">unable to afford legal advice and representation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">no longer have access to free legal services to resolve </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a whole host of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">problems </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">that affect their </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">daily lives, including (but not limited to),</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> private family disputes, education, employment and social welfare related problems. At a time where the coalition government are also slashing costs in local government</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> reforming a number of public services</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and pushing ahead with other welfare reform plans</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">These cuts were widely opposed and condemned by many groups and individuals, including </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">MiCLU</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, on the basis that they prevent the poor and marginalised communities </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">of England and Wales from accessing justice who would otherwise have a perfectly clear entitlement to legal redress, but were unfortunate enough to not be in a position to pay the exorbitant rates so easily met </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">by</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> affluent members of society </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> government</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> departments and large private enterprises.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The impact of the cuts have been disturbing and in our </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">own </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">practice we are witnessing the individual suffering of many now unable to understand and address the maze of law, policy and practice that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">govern their</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> lives</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span></li></ol><h1 style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">13.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">In the Consultation to the LASPO Bill, the coalition government stated that the proposed amendments, most of which are now in force</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal"> would </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal; text-decoration:underline">complete</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal"> an overhaul to the civil and criminal justice systems</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">. However, on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">8 April 2013</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal"> just days after the new Act took effect, the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">government introduced these new</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal"> proposals, which are not subject to the same parliamentary scrutiny and yet significantly impact upon access to justice for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">members of civil society. </span></h1><h1 style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">14.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">In our view it</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal"> is legitimat</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">e to query why these proposals, which must have been subject to internal consideration and consultation for a significantly appropriate period given their impact, were not involved in the LASPO process. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">Gi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">ven the gravity of impact on access to justice</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal"> for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">many members of society</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">why are such proposals </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">not subject to the same statutory processes as LASPO? Instead the coalition Government chose to announce the proposals </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">on the apron strings of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">LASPO </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">providing </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">only</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal"> a short consultation period for interested p</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">arties and the general public to respond (9th April – 4 June 2013). </span></h1><h1 style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">15.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">The</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal"> coalition government </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">has made sweeping statement</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal"> to justify the need for the proposals, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">suggest</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">ing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal"> that the aims of the proposal are aimed at</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal"> </span></h1><h1 style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 54pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">Improving</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal"> public confidence in the legal aid scheme’</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">. </span></h1><h1 style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 54pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">Saving costs to the public purse and the taxpayer</span></h1><h1 style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 54pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"></span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">To not allow those ‘who have never set foot in England or Wales, or those who have never paid taxes in the UK’ to benefit financially from the civil legal aid </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">scheme’</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a></h1><h1 style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">16.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">However, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">most of the assertions lack any firm evidential basis or foundation. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">We submit that there has been a wholesale failure on the part of the coalition government </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">to properly satisfy itself, and the public, of the likely impact such proposals</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal"> will have on society, the public purse and most of all on the rights of individuals with protected characteristics and vulnerable groups, particularly children and young people. </span></h1><h1 style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">17.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">W</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">e are not aware of any evidence which purports to argue that there is a lack of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">public confidence in the legal aid scheme,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal"> nor has such evidence been made available during the consultation or the subsequent response to the proposals. To the contrary, we un</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">derstand that there has been a wealth of responses to the consultation to argue that leaving marginalised and/or vulnerable children and people </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">without access to justice would in fact leave them </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">open to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal"> abuse by the government, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">unable to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">enforce their lega</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">l rights </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">and/or at worst place such groups at risk of harm, exploitation or abuse. We believe that allowing access to justice for the most vulnerable </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">would </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">in fact </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">serve to increase confidence in the legal aid system.</span></h1><h1 style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">18.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">In fact, the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">coalition </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">Government has </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">refused to publish the percentage breakdowns showing how many of the 16,000 responses they received to the consultation were supportive or opposed to the proposals, with the Justice Minster evading the qu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">estion when asked in Parliament</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">. However, it is cle</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">ar from all published responses to the consultation, as well as the media reporting of this issue, that these proposals were met with significant opposition</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">, including the judiciary and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal"> the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal"> government’s own lawyers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:normal">.</span></h1><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We consider that these current proposed </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">changes constitute an ideological shift, which will cause grave constitutional consequences for access to justice to the most vulnerable in our society, is an attack on this country’s most important egalitarian constitutional principles and undermines the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">rule of law.</span></li></ol><h1 style="background-color:#ffffff; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 18pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">B.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The demise of legal advice provision for local communities and vulnerable members of society</span></h1><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">As a legal charity we have been loathed to address the issue around ‘financial sustainability’ for fear of being judged as professionals merely </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">opp</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">osing the cuts and the new proposals to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">protect our jobs. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">However, it would be unfair to the communities </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and clients </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">we represent not to explain and highlight the current landscape in which legal advice provision is operating and the decline in services ar</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ound the UK. For this reason, we think it is vital that the Committee have a true picture of what impact the cuts are having,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and are likely to have,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> not only on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the lives of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">individual members of society, but our communities as a whole.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="16" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">As noted above, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">despite strong opposition</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the Government has pressed ahead with instituting the cuts to legal aid contained in LASPO. In turn this has required private providers, NGOs and charities, including the Law Centre movement of which </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">we are</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> a member, to institute</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> wholesale restructuring </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">programmes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> in an effort to continue to function in a post-LASPO environment. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="17" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">When the LASPO changes were being planned the legal sector was required to refocus its remaining resources on work that it believed would remain in scop</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e while trying to develop innovative ways of continuing to assist its other vulnerable clients, who did not cease to exist simply because funding for their cases had ceased. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="18" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Civil legal aid providers had to renegotiate their contracts with the Legal Serv</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ices Commission (as it then was and now the Legal Aid Agency) in advance of the start of the new regime under LASPO, and the level of internal reorganization has resulted in a wave of redundancies of skilled legal practitioners nationally, with others taki</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ng early retirement or having to retrain. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="19" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Having conducted this </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">reorganisation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, the sector moved into its post-LASPO future with much trepidation, but with the hope that a basic level of service could be maintained for the many vulnerable groups that it </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">had been working to support.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> However, the impact of LASPO has been far reaching and coupled with the new proposals the survival of legal practices working for local communities is under </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">serious</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> threat.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">A recent survey conducted by the S</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">olicitors </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">R</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">egulatory </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">uthority (SRA)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, and reported in the Law Society Gazette, indicated that around 1200 solicitor’s firms </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">performing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> legal aid and personal injury work around the country are now classed as ‘showing evidence of financial difficulty’</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Of these, some</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> 500 were listed as ‘high impact’ firms, which would have a significant impact on the market and high intervention</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> cost if they were to fail. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The SRA</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> did n</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ot include the charitable and Not for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">P</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">rofit</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> sectors</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> in their survey</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, of which </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">we form a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">part</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, w</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">hich are facing the same pressures but who lack the financial resources and market flexibility to respond in the same way as our private sector colleagues</span><span style="color:#575757; font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Many Law </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Centres</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and small-medium </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">sized high street practices have been forced to close</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> their doors</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to the public. By way of example, we have recently </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">witnessed the closure of Birmingham Law Centre, England’s second biggest city with one of the largest migrant populations in the UK. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Earlier this month, we saw the closure of Streetwise Community Law Cent</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">re a pan-London expert legal advice service for young people aged between 16 to 25 years offering legal advice and representation in housing, education, welfare benefits, debt and community care. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> fact tha</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">t funding cuts are making such</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> service</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> unsust</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ainable means that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the coalition</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> government are effectively failing our</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> children,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> young people</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and communities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">It is our belief that these new proposals will exacerbate this problem, are actively discriminatory and cannot be defende</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">d as an exercise in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">cost saving.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="A" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.43pt; padding-left:3.57pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The impact of proposals </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">on protected persons and public expenditure</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">As stated above, we believe that there has been a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> general failure on the part of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">G</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">overnment to properly satisfy itself, and the public, of the likely impact such proposals will have on society, the public purse and most of all on the rights of individuals with protected characteristics and vulnerable groups, particularly children and yo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ung people. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="25" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Nothing can be starker than the concerns raised by the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Association of Directors for Children’s Services, the Local Government Association and the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">coalition of Local Authorities forming the No Recourse to Public Funds </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Network </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">(NRPF) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">who believ</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> savings to the public purse envisaged by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Central government through these proposals</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> may in fact be wiped out by increased costs to other statutory services</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="26" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Recent assessments by the NRPF network, with whom </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">we</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> were </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">partnered, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">has </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">addressed this i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ssue </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">in great detail having conducted shadow equality and financial impact assessments</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In the interests of space and time </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">we will not repeat the findings here.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="27" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We have annexed the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">findings to our evidence and would merely reiterate the point that from </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">these findings, and other studies undertaken</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, these proposals would not only fail to save money, they are highly likely to greatly increase costs for the taxpayer</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> by shifting costs to other statutory service providers, in turn placing a heavy burden on pu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">blic spending.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="28" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Furthermore, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the shadow equality impact assessment illustrates that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the proposals are likely to prejudice a whole host of groups in society with protected characteristics. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Although, it is worth noting here that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">we are astonished that the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Mo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">J</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> has not carried out a Child Impact Assessment as part of their Equality Impact Assessment</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> process</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">thereby failing in its entirety to consider the dangers posed to the health, development, wellbeing and lives of many migrant children and young people in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the UK (many who were born here and/or have spent most of their lives </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">here</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">). The gravity of the proposals cannot be underestimated and we fear that if these proposals go ahead the Government is placing many children </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and young people </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">at risk of serious harm</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We now turn to the new proposals. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="A" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 33.41pt; padding-left:2.59pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The proposed introduction of a residence test for civil legal aid claimants</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="29" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The UK justice system operates on the constitutional principle that all within its jurisdiction are equal before the law. Yet the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">MoJ</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> has pro</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">posed a two limb residence test </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">before</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> allow</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> access </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to civil legal aid of any kind.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> To qualify a person must be able to show that they are:</span></li><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.78pt; padding-left:4.22pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">“Lawfully resident in the UK, Crown Dependencies or British Overseas Territories at the time</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the application for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">civil legal aid was made; and”</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 68.33pt; padding-left:3.67pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">They have</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> “resided lawfully in the UK, Crown Dependencies or British Overseas Territories for a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">continuous period of at least 12 months at any point in the past</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="30" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This test would be administered by lawyers as part of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">bureaucracy attendant on any application for legal aid, requiring untrained lawyers to assess and apply complex immigration assessments to determine eligibility.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Lawyers who will be asked to administer the process will have little, if any, expertise in imm</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">igration law and would </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">therefore </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">not be competent to assess</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">immigration status themselves and many people will struggle to find the evidence</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">needed to show they meet the test</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">VC is an elderly lady who originates from Jamaica and has lived in the UK sinc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">e around 1965. She was brought to the UK to join her parents who arrived in the first decade after the Second World War. As VC entered the UK before the Immigration Act 1971 she has a statutory right to settle permanently in the UK. She has worked in the U</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">K as a nurse in the NHS for many years. He</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">r</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> passport was destroyed in a house fire some years ago. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Many</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> of our other elderly UK residents have rights of permanent settlement even if they arrived post- 1971. The difficulty is that the Home Office inform t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">hey do not keep records of foreign nationals granted historic settlement as they are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">obliged to destroy papers pursuant to the Data Protection Act. Over many decades our own clients </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">may have </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">lost </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">their </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">passports, other ID documents and endorsements and can</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">not prove they are lawfully in the UK. This category of very vulnerable older resident is often incredibly </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">marginalised</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and under the new provisions would immediately fall foul of the residence test and fail to engage a lawyer for a judicial review action.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="32" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The proposals do not exclude British people that meet the test, but many in our communities do not travel and do not have a passport. A birth certificate does not confer nationality. Obtaining a passport is expensive and it is reasonable to envisage a li</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">kely scenario of a family requiring homelessness assistance in circumstances where no- one in that family has a passport. The proposals will seriously prejudice the most economically and socially disadvantaged British people. It will also prejudice elderly</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> people from the Commonwealth and elsewhere who have lived, worked and voted in the UK for most of their lives, in circumstances where it becomes apparent that they have lost their original passport, which included an immigration stamp confirming they were</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> entitled to settle here when they entered the UK or they entered prior to the coming into force of the 1971 Act, which means they are settled automatically but do not have the evidence for it. At ILC we have seen many such cases concerning people who came</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to the UK in the two or three post- war decades, as family members of Caribbean parents who were invited and came to the after the war. This lost generation of post- war Commonwealth citizens increasingly faces huge prejudices in accessing employment, ret</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">irement, health and other facilities. In a recent freedom of information request submitted by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Lambeth</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Law Centre it was confirmed that the Home Office do not retain records of those granted settlement many years ago. In such cases the Home Office writes to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> applicants and MPs to advise seeking legally aided assistance. Yet, under these proposals this group would not be able to receive such advice.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="33" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Furthermore, we are also concerned that, in conjunction with other moves the government are proposing to introd</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">uce, such as immigration checks by private landlords and medical </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">centres</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, our society is increasingly moving towards the imposition of an ID card system by the back door. Parliament has seen several attempts by the previous government to institute a compul</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">sory ID card scheme, all of which have been repulsed, and we had understood that it was the current government’s policy not to introduce an ID card scheme. However, their moves over furthering immigration control into everyday life, such as private renting</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, but also in relation to the question of accessing legal advice, will render it necessary for everyone to confirm their identification at all times. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="34" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Conversely, many children and young people </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">we represent are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">born in the UK</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> are British </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Citizens </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">or hav</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e an entitlement to register as British Citizens under </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the British Nationality Act 1981. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The laws around nationality law are varied and complex. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Many </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">children </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">have parents who are British citizens. If they are unable to afford the application fee, or have simply not ever needed to apply for a passport because of a lack of funds and/or because their means do not allow them to travel abroad, they will fall foul of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the test and will be unable to access legal aid. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Matthew is 8 years old and has been diagnosed with attention deficit hyperactivity disorder (ADHD). He is having difficulties at school and his mother</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> Jean</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> is unable to access support from his school to help the family cope and ensure that he reaches his potential. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The Local Authority have also threatened to take </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Matthew</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> into care. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Jean </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">has no documents confirming her nationality and that of Matthew. Jean’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">parents were</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> Jamaican national</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">s but she remembers that they had British passports.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> However, Jean has never applied for a passport because she </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">never needed one and the family never had the money to go on holiday.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="35" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Equally, many EEA nationals will be unable</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to prove their lawful residence and an unqualified lawyer may not understand the complexities of immigration law surrounding the rights and entitlements of EEA nationals.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Maria is 22 year old Spanish national. She has returned to the UK to work and has b</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">een in the UK for 7 months. Before returning to Spain she had studied and worked in the UK</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> for a year</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">. She has recently given birth to her small baby and has been told that she is being evicted. Maria has lived in the UK for 12 months but has no documentar</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">y evidence to prove how long she has been here. As a Spanish national she also has no visa or immigration document to prove her status.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="36" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We consider that the residence test is simply unworkable and will result in British people and migrants with the requis</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ite minimum of 12 months lawful leave being refused access to legally aided advice services, in any event.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="37" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">As can be seen from the above examples, m</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">any people will simply not have the evidence required by the LAA and will be unable e.g. to pay for a Briti</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">sh passport on an expedited basis simply to satisfy the evidential needs of the LAA. This issue could of itself cause challenges to the LAA and MOJ. For example, a British family with no history of migration to the UK who do not have passports require urge</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">nt legally aided advice and assistance as the council is about to evict them from their home. They go to a solicitor who asks to see proof of nationality, but as the family have never held passports and otherwise have no way to prove nationality (birth in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the UK does not prove nationality) the lawyer tells them that they will need to check the position with the LAA. If they are turned away they could </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">become homeless or a lawyer may take on the case at risk but with the prospect of satellite litigation again</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">st the LAA/MOJ.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="38" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In addition, it will not always be easy to ascertain whether individuals and families meet the residence test, and as the test applies across all civil areas of law- housing, family, community care, education gateway etc. non- immigration </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">lawyers would be expected to calculate whether a potential legal aid beneficiary has been lawfully resident in the UK for 12 months. This is not as simple as checking passports and visas. For example, EU law confers rights on EU members and third country f</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">amily members resident in the UK, and there is no requirement for the EU member or family member to apply to the Home Office for an EEA Residence Card, which is mere confirmation of a right that is derived not from the Home Office but from the EU Treaty an</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">d associated Directives. These rights often involve complicated factual scenarios where a non- immigration lawyer will not have the expertise to undertake a full analysis.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="39" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We believe that restricting civil legal aid in the manner proposed under both </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">proposed limbs of the test raise significant concerns</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> for access to justice</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and the introduction of the test would undermine the rule of law. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="40" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We are highly concerned that the notion of a residence test has been introduced into policy thinking with little</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> if any regard for its implications. At a basic level, it is concerning that by</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">their </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">own admission the government are unable to estimate even roughly how many cases would be affected by the residence test</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="41" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">As an organization that is centered around the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">needs of migrant children and young people, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">MiCLU</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> is particularly concerned by the evident lack of concern for the impact that these proposed changes are likely to have on children or, indeed, any indication that the UK’s responsibilities under the UN Conv</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ention on the Rights of the Child have been factored into Ministerial thinking.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="42" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">MoJ’s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> response to the consultation, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">‘Transforming Legal Aid: Next Steps’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, it announced a number of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">revisions</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to the general residence test</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> rule, and have now sought to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">apply the following exceptions to the residence test: </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Children under 12 months old</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> who are lawfully resident in the UK</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Current a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">sylum seekers (seeking rights under </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">para</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> 30(1), Schedule 1 LASPO)</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Detention cases (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">paras</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> 5, 20, 25, 26 and 27 – and judicial r</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">eview under </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">para</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> 19 where</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> one is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">challenging lawfulness of detention – Schedule 1 LASPO)</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Trafficking </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">cases where there is a positive decision from the National Referral Mechanism </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">(</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">para</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> 32, Schedule 1 LASPO)</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Certain domestic violence and forced marriage cas</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">es (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">paras</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> 11, 12, 13, 16, 28 and 29, Schedule 1LASPO)</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Child protection cases (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">paras</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> 1, 10, 15 and 23, Schedule 1 LASPO </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and also </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">paras</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> 3 and 9, but only </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">in respect to child victims)</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Limited access to judicial review of certifications under s.94 and 96 of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the Nationality,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Immigration and Asylum Act 2002.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Armed forces personnel and their immediate families</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Special Immigration Appeals Commission (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">para</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> 24, Schedule 1 LASPO)</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="43" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">When the original consultation was announced we were concerned that the residence tes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">t had little regard for the actual legal position or practical impact that such a change would have. Having now seen the ‘revised’ version of the residence test we are convinced that this is the case.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="44" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We submit that the proposed revisions, listed above, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">do not in any meaningful way deal with the substance of the criticisms put to the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">MoJ</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to the original proposal. Instead, they appear to combine a checklist approach from pre-existing legislation (in the case of the clauses relating to trafficking, domestic</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> violence and child protection, which merely reins</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">tate the LASPO provisions) with</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> a failure to fully engage with the logic of their own positions</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">(in the case of the baby and refugee concessions</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. As a result, we believe that, while in our view the general</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ized cuts </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> legal aid in LASPO were damaging and contrary to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the UK’s duties under the ECHR, EU law and the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">UNCRC, these revisions will fail to protect even the small minority of claimants that they purport to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">assist</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="45" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We will seek to address the proposed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> revisions first and then comment upon the group of people, including children and young people, who continue to fall foul of the proposals</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> outside of the revisions</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.8pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">i)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Revised provisions - ‘Transforming Legal Aid: Next Steps’</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.8pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="46" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The concession for babies under 12 months old is intended to deal with the problem, highlighted repeatedly in responses to ‘Transforming Legal Aid’ that new-born infants would be placed in the absurd position of going without independent legal representati</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">on to protect their interests in a context where both the State and the parents are likely to be fully represented. The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">MoJ</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> has sought to allay these concerns by introducing two concessions, one reinstating legal aid for all babies that are legally residen</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">t in the UK and one reinstating legal aid for all children in protection cases. While this, on one reading, might appear </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to unnecessarily double-up the protection required to respond to this criticism, it does in fact leave a sub-group of babies who will r</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">emain without legal representation when the state clearly has a legal duty to provide it. These are babies that for whatever reason are unlawfully resident in the UK but are not parties in a protection case. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">For example, a child was born in the UK to a non</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">-national parent who requires urgent services from a Local Authority but those services are not provided and a challenge against their refusal is necessary to protect them. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Sima</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> is a Pakistani national who arrived into the UK when she was 2 years old. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">She is now 18 an</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">d has given birth to a baby outside </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">of wedlock. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The baby’s father is also a Pakistani national. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Neighbours</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">have raised concerns </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">about the baby and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Sima</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">with the Local Authority. The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Local Authority have visited the family home and are satis</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">fied that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Sima</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> and the baby are looked after by the family</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> and there are no child protection issues</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">. This </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">is largely as a result of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> language barriers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> and misleading information that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Sima’s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> family have provided</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">. The Local Authority </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">decide not</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> to intervene. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Sima</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> wants to remain</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> in the family home</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">does not wish for the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> child to remain with her. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">She is also concerned about the child’s welfare and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">would like someone to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">help</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> the baby</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> but she will not shame the family by disclosing any information </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">about the fa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">mily circumstances</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">nor will she initiate</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> any proceedings</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> against them</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="47" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">There is no lawful basis for the deprivation of such a child’s access to legally- aided advice in circumstances where it is incontrovertibly clear most children have no capacity </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">or means to otherwise access legal representation. It is legally incomprehensible that for example, a migrant child who was born in the UK will be denied State access to independent legal advice to ensure that their best interests and welfare are advanced </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">in an adversarial </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">welfare and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">court system. Or that the same child would not be afforded a legal representative in circumstances where a local authority was refusing relevant statutory assistance, particularly in the context of our family jurisdiction, whi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ch has at its core, a child’s best interests as a paramount consideration.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="48" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Taking the concession relating to refugees (or ‘successful asylum seekers’ as the consultation refers to them) as another example, the original consultation document proposed that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">legal aid would be retained for substantive asylum claims but that once granted lawful leave to remain as a refugee, applicants would have to wait a year before being entitled to any further legal aid for matters outside of their substantive asylum claim. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">MoJ’s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> response has been to extend the exemption </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> those granted Refugee status </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">by stating that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">their required 12 month period of lawful leave </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to fall within the residence test will be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">calculated from the date they submitted their asylum claim, rather </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">than the date when that claim for asylum is accepted</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="49" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The grant of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">refugee status is clearly a significantly positive event in the life of an asylum seeker,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> however in our experience</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> it is also attendant with major upheavals, caused by the termination of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> their entitlement to asylum support and accommodation. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Abdi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> is an unaccompanied asylum seeking child from Somalia. He witnessed the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">massacre</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> of his </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">immediate </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">family</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> whilst in Somalia</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">. He was separated from his uncle </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">subjected to abuse and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">ill-treatment on his journey to a safe country</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">. He arrived alone in the UK. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">He was 17 years old on arrival and placed in Local Authority care. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">His </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">claim for asylum was accepted a few</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> months after his arrival and he was granted refugee status</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">he was</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> ‘lawfu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">lly present’ in the UK as an asylum-seeker for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">2 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">months and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">‘lawfully resident’ in the UK as a refugee for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">a further 2 months)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">. On turning 18, the Local Au</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">thority advise</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> him that they w</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">ill</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> no longer responsible for his care. His support and accommodation w</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">as terminated and he was given no assistance with accessing alternative support and housing. He became </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">street homeless. There was a significant deterioration</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> in his </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">mental </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">health, requiring urgent </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">medical intervention.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="50" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Legal</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> aid is often required to assist </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">refugees</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> in securing </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">necessary support and services</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and for separated children the need for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">support and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">services under the Children Act provisions</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> that they are entitled to. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Melissa is 14 years old from Albania. She was </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">trafficked into the UK at the age of 12 for the purposes of sexual exploitation. The police raid the brothel that she is imprisoned in and she is taken into the protection of the Local Authority.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The Local Authority think that she is 16 and not 15 but pla</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">ce in her </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">foster care </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">for her protection. He</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">r claim for asylum is successful and she is granted refugee status within 2 months of her claim being submitted. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">A few weeks after securing refugee status t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">he Local Authority decide to terminate her foster placem</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">ent and place her in semi-independent accommodation. Melissa is doing well in foster care and her foster mother is helping her to recover from her experiences and does not think it would be in Melissa’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">s best interests</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> to be alone and in semi-supervised acc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">ommodation. She also believes that Melissa is 14 not 16. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">John is a 17 year old from Uganda. He was forcibly recruited as a child </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">soldier </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">to fight with rebel groups where he suffered and witnessed severe incidents of violence and human rights abuses. He h</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">as significant mental health problems and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">suffers from Post-Traumatic Stress Disorder. He is granted international protection after being interviewed by the Home Office, approximately 7 months after his arrival to the UK. His health is deteriorating and th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">e Local Authority failed to access relevant support to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">help him with his mental health</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> needs </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">(he was ‘lawfully present’ in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">the UK as an asylum-seeker for 7</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> months and ‘lawfully resident’ in the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">UK as a refugee for a further month</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="51" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We submit</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> that failure to provide legal aid </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to refugees </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">would result in lawfully resident </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">refugees</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> being rendered homeless </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">or lack the relevant support and services </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">they need </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to help them recover from their past experiences and thus</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> place the UK in a position of vi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">olating Article 3 E</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">uropean </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">C</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">onvention on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">H</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">uman </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">R</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ights (ECHR) as well as children’s rights embodied in the UN Convention on the Rights of the Child (UNCRC) particularly, articles 3, 19, 24 and 37</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Government has</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> a responsibility to make sure children’s righ</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ts are respected, protected and fulfilled</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and that their survival, development and health needs are met, including access to services to allow them to ensure such rights are given effect and measures implemented to protect such rights.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Ali is a 16 year ol</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">d unaccompanied asylum seeking child from Afghanistan who claimed asylum and was granted refugee status within 8 months of his arrival to the UK.  He is unable to access the relevant support to go to college and his social worker has failed to assist him w</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">ith making relevant applications for bursaries and to assist him with accessing relevant college courses. He has been able to secure a place for himself at a college that is 5 miles away but the Local Authority have advised him that they are unable to assi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">st him with travel expenses. He feels very isolated and is depressed. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="52" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">MoJ’s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> response which, as noted above, is to start counting the eligibility for legal aid from the date of an asylum claim rather than the date of the grant, however, does next to n</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">othing to resolve these problems.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">A </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">recognised</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Refugee should not have to wait for 12 months from the date of their asylum claim to avail themselves of legal aid where they have e.g. legitimate housing, community care and family law matters to contend with. Conferring Refugee status to asy</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">lum claimants does not stop vulnerability. The proposals will stop child refugees, victims of torture and political exiles fighting for democracy from accessing legal representation once the very cause of their reason to flee their home country has been </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">le</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">gitimised</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="53" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The proposals are unfair, unequal, disproportionate, discriminatory and irrational, and they fly in the face of the UK’s standing as a country that respects and protects the rights of Refugees, not just in the grant of international protection</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, but in their treatment thereafter</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">at a time when they </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">may be</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> extremely vulnerable and require access to servic</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">es to assist with their recovery.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The proposals provide for serious disadvantages to established Refugees, who on the grant of Refugee status </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">continue to benefit from protections in the Refugee Convention, European and other international instruments such as the UNCRC. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The proposals clearly contravene Article 16.2 of the UN Refugee Convention on the basis that Refugees will be disadvantaged in t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">erms of access to legal aid in circumstances where a British national with equivalent circumstances would not. Article 16.2 of the Refugee Convention, guarantees that: </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">A refugee shall enjoy in the Contracting State in which he has his habitual residence </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">the same treatment as a national in matters pertaining to access to the Courts, including legal assistance</span></p><ol start="54" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Home Office </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">maintain </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">that they seek to ensure that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> 90% of asylum claims should be resolved within six months of their commencement. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">On the govern</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ment’s own </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">assertion, therefore</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, we </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">calculate</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> that this proposal will mean that 42% of all those that lodge an initial claim for asylum will be unlawfully denied legal aid, to resolve crucial human rights issues relating to destitution</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, access to services</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and discrimination in contravention of the Refugee Convention, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">EU law, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the ECHR and the UK’s obligations under UNCRC. This estimate is based on an asylum success rate (initial claim and tribunal appeal combined) of 47.07%</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> meeting the government policy of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">90% resolution within six months.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="55" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We welcome the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">MoJ’s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> concession to accept that ‘fresh claims’ will continue to receive legal aid to be ‘prepared and submitted’, rather than the original proposal which appeared to only allow for claims to be eligible for</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> legal aid once they had been accepted by the Home Office. However, the response seems to suggest that legal aid will only be available to ‘prepare the application’ but unclear as to whether the ‘asylum seekers exemption’ will benefit fresh claim applicant</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s in its entirety i.e. to access other forms of civil legal aid whilst their fresh asylum claim is being prepared. We would ask that the Committee request clarification from the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">MoJ</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> in this respect. Should the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">MoJ</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> respond in the negative, we submit that th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e residence test discriminates between the exception for initial asylum seekers, conferring no such exception for fresh claim applicants, whom the Supreme Court has ruled should be treated equally in law. Domestic and EU law </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">recognises</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> that fresh claim asy</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">lum applicants fall under the definition of ‘asylum applicants’ pursuant to the Refugee Convention and EU law, and should not otherwise be practicably prejudiced. In the case of ZO (Somalia) the UK Supreme Court held that asylum applications should not be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">treated as having been subject to a final decision until all possible remedies have been pursued and determined, including decisions and appeals arising out of fresh claims. Accordingly, the description of an “asylum applicant” in the EU Reception Directiv</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e must be interpreted to include a person who is making a subsequent application, or “fresh claim.” </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="56" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Turning to the other </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">revisions recently announced for</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">victims of trafficking; domestic violence and cases involving child protection,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> which</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> simply reinstate legal aid along the lines provided by LASPO. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="57" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Cases involving the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">care, supervision and protection of children as well as victims of child abuse </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">(child protection cases) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">will </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">continue to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">receive funding, but these cases are limited to th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ose defined in LASPO and therefore do not relate to immigration cases involving children where equivalent matters are at issue.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="58" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">By using the case examples of Ali, Melissa and John above – they are all separated children who have been in care of the Local </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Authority under s20 of the Children Act 1989. They do not fall within the ambit of child protection cases to fall within the scope of the residence test. They clearly require assistance from community care lawyers to help them access to relevant support an</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">d services to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">help them recover from their pas</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">t experiences, assist with their health and developmental needs</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="59" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Likewise, vulnerable migrant children who have been taken into the care of Children’s services by virtue of s20  of the Children Act 1989, and w</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ho have not made a claim for asylum – also fall foul of the child protection revision be</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">cause they are not subject to the various orders under the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Children Act 1989</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> cited under LASPO</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Vera is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> 12 year old Angolan child who was brought into the UK when s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">he was a baby by her Portuguese national sister. Her </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">sister no longer want</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">care for</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> her and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">takes her to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">the Local A</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">uthority. The Local Authority </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">provide Vera with care and support under s20 of the Children Act 1989. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">There is evidence of abuse but as Ve</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">ra is already in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">the care of children’s services</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> the Local Authority do not pursue a care order under s31</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Vera is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">out into a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> foster placement. The school have raised concerns about Vera’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">s wellbeing, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">general appearance</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> and concentration levels at school</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">. Vera tells </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">her teacher </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">she is not getting along with the children in the foster family and social services have not listened to her. It transpires that the foster </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">carer</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">also </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">no longer </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">willing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> to support Vera but has not been able to get any help from </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">social services to address the care placement. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Stuart arrived into the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">UK </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">with his mother </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">when he was 5 years old. He is a Nigerian national. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Social services have been involved with the family because of concerns raised about his welfare. He is placed on</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> the child protection register. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Stuart is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">later </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">abandoned by his mother </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">and her whereabouts are unknown. She has left him with</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> strangers </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">where he is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">subject to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> abuse and neglect. He is placed in the care of the Local Authority under s20 of the Children Act</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> 1989. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="60" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In both cases, Vera and Stuart have no immigration status and cannot show that they have been in the UK lawfully for a period of 12 months. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In our experience, migrant children who are in the care of a Local Authority are rarely subject to a care o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">rder under s31 of the Children Act 1989. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The number of cases involving migrant children in Local Authority care without lawful status is likely to increase under LASPO because immigration cases have been taken out of the scope of legal aid, including for s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">eparated children. Local Authorities are therefore unable to access free legal advice for these children and so their irregular status may remain unresolved and under the new proposals they will be unable to access free legal advice for any legal problems </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">they face as children in care. Local Authorities owe these children various duties and responsibilities under the Children Act 1989 but many are unwilling and/or feel unable to access privately funded immigration advice for these children</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, largely because </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">of cuts in resources</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">MiCLU</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> has worked closely with a number of social workers who are concerned about the current lack of legal advice for these children and as </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">far as </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">we understand there is no policy and/or guidance formulated to address concerns around </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">irregular status of separated children in Local Authority care.  The legality of LASPO in cases involving separated and unaccompanied children is in our opinion unlawful and breaches the rights of children under Article 8 of the ECHR, EU law and the UN</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">CRC. We are astonished that the government proposes to bring </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">in further cuts that will stop these vulnerable children’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">access to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">any</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">civil </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">legal aid </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">– especially where the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">legality of previous changes are yet to be determined.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="61" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The revision relating to v</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ictims of domestic violence </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">remaining</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> eligible for legal aid, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the revision only relates to certain categories, such as</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> victims who have</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> had entered the UK on a spousal visa. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In our view this is a wholesale failure on the part of government, once again</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">recognize that victims of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">domestic </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">violence are not only spouses</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and partners but often vulnerable members of the family such as children and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">elderly</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and/or other dependent relatives</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We submit that these changes are i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ndirectly discriminate against other v</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ictims of domestic violence </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and that the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> new provisions would force sufferers, particularly young people, to stay in an abusive family unit and subject any children to the relationship to on- going direct or indirect abuse and harm.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Daphne is 19 year old </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">from Malawi and arrives as a dependent of her mother. Her mother secures a visa to join her new partner in the UK. She has learning difficulties and is particularly dependent on her mother as a result. Whilst in the UK she is subjected to violence at the h</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">ands of her </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">mother and her n</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">ew partner. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">She tells someone at the church</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> what is happening to her and they try to get her some help from the Local </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Authority. The Local Authority inform members of the faith group that they are unable to help Daphne because s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">he is not a child and over 18.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 72pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Deborah is a 15 year old Jamaican national. She arrived into the UK when she was 6 years old and joined her British family. The details of her arrival and status are unknown. She has tried to commit suicide and is self-harm</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">ing. She discovers she is pregnant and runs away from home. Her teacher contacts the Local Authority because she is worried about her housing situation and also </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">notices the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">deterioration in Deborah’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">s health. Deborah discloses a history of sexual abuse with</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">in the family home since childhood. The case is referred to the police and investigations are on-going. She has been told by the police and the Local Authority that she has no immigration status in the UK and therefore must return to Jamaica if she can. Th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">e only home that Deborah has known is the UK. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="62" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Likewise, attempts to reinstate victims of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">trafficking’s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> rights to legal aid simply by re-imposing the limits placed on them by LASPO will do nothing to provide the kind of legal assistance that is required b</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">y trafficking victims and to which they are entitled under the UN Convention Against Trafficking and the Council of Europe Convention on Action Against Human Trafficking</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (CAT)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. The assumption that legal aid can be provided at the point at which a trafficki</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ng victim is granted a ‘reasonable grounds’ decision, as prescribed by LASPO Schedule 1, Part 1 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">para</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (1)(b), fails to engage with the requirement to compile sufficient evidence and present often relatively complex legal arguments to demonstrate why the tra</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">fficking convention applies in a given case. In contrast to the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">MoJ’s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> apparent assumption of a malfunctioning and delayed asylum system, discussed above, this proposal appears to depend on a hopelessly optimistic assessment of the capacity of the Trafficki</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ng determination system to function smoothly, fairly and effectively. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="63" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The recent case of R (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Atamewan</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">) v. Secretary of State for the Home Department [2013] EWHC 2727 (Admin) demonstrates that even receiving what might be thought of as an initial decision, such as a reasonable grounds decision, in relation to trafficking is fa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">r from straightforward. This case revealed that for several years the Home Office have been using a policy that unlawfully precluded a significant proportion of trafficking victims, those that could be described as having ‘a historic claim’, from the prote</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ction provided by the Convention against Trafficking. We believe that this demonstrates that not only does securing a reasonable grounds decision in a trafficking case require concerted legal efforts to ensure that the necessary evidence is submitted, but </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">it will also require skilled </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">legal representation </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to ensure that the legal requirements in the CAT are abided by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">by</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the Home Office, a branch of government with an unfortunate record for failing to abide by its duties under law. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="64" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We believe that these co</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ncessions, along with the others not discussed in such </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">detail</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> in our evidence</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, demonstrate the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">MoJ’s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> rush to proceed with these ill-thought out plans. Moreover, this rush has caused them to take a worryingly slapdash approach to the thoroughly justified co</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ncerns expressed to them by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">many who oppose the changes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">who </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">have </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">warn</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ed them that their proposals ar</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e likely to be unlawful with regard to the ECHR, the UN Refugee Convention, the UNCRC and the European Convention Against Trafficking in Human Beings. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.8pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ii)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Legality of the residence test</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.8pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="65" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We submit that the residence test is unlawful in its entirety, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">both </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">in its application to adults and children.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="66" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">On </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">point of principle, the residence test would fundamentally undermine the operation of the rule of law in the UK. It is an established constitutional principle that there must be equality before the law, and denying legal aid to people who have received unl</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">awful treatment at the hands of public bodies in the UK, seriously strikes at the legitimacy of our justice system. It cannot reasonably be asserted that vulnerable members of our society with no financial resources, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">often a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">consequence of various vulnerab</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ilities, should not have the right to access assistance in making legitimate complaints and claims to public authorities, which have significant resources and in-house legal teams. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We do not accept that a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> wrong committed </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">by the UK state </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">against a person th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e government deems to have </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">insufficient ties to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the UK </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a lesser wrong? </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="67" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In our view the ministers responsible for the residency test policy have attempted </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to obscure the impact on justice and the rule of law that removal of legal aid will have. The pro</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">posals exist in a land of make-believe in which legal rights can continue to be asserted without any financial resources or legal expertise. The reality is that removal of legal aid will mean removal of legal rights for these groups of people. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">All people </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">n the UK must </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">have the right to hold the UK government and its agencies to account when wrongs are committed.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="68" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Despite assertions to the contrary, (by way of the inclusion of British nationals), the test is clearly discriminatory and we consider it may fal</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">l foul of discrimination laws and provisions, as it will:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Disproportionately affect migrants and children</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, and will</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> therefore indirectly discriminate against those with a particular race, age, ethnicity or nationality. This has implications pursuant to th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e Equality Act 2010 and Article 14 ECHR (when considered alongside Article 6 ECHR).</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">b)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Directly discriminate against all children who do not meet the proposed test, including (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">) British children under the age of 12 months who are unable to prove their citiz</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">enship entitlement, (ii) migrant children who have been lawfully resident in the UK for less than 12 months and (iii) migrant children unlawfully resident in the UK who as minors without legal capacity or financial resources, cannot be held culpable for fa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">iling to seek to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">regularise</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> their status or seek privately- paid legal advice. It is no answer that local authorities can foot the financial bill, as in many cases such vulnerable and undocumented children will not be known to social services and even if t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">hey are, social workers are not immigration law experts and often do not </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">recognise</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the advice needs of migrant children and young people. Local authority in- house teams are prohibited from providing immigration law advice, as advisors are not OISC registe</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">red.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> There would also be serious questions regarding conflicts of interest and competing instructions if in-house local authority teams were to take on such work. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">c)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">D</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">irectly and/ or indirectly discriminate against EEA nationals and their family members, ma</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ny of whom derive lawful rights of residence through the interpretation of EU law by domestic and international courts, in circumstances where not all rights have been comprehensively incorporated into domestic law.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">ii</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">The residence test- not fit for pu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">rpose</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="69" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The residence test is couched in terms whereby it is not capable of doing what the proposals assert it is intended to do</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">provide legal aid for people with a “strong connection to the UK.” Strength of connection cannot reasonably be asserted on the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">basis of lawful residence or length of residence, historic or current, without a thorough assessment on a case by case basis of UK-based ties.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="70" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">There are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">also </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">additional reasons why it breaches children’s rights in particular.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">At </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">MiCLU</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> we act for many children and young people who were brought into the UK by family at a very young age and subsequently have “overstayed” e.g. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">beyond </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the period allowed say by a visitor visa, or as the dependent on a parent’s student visa, in circum</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">stances where they had no knowledge or control over decisions concerning their entry to the UK, immigration issues and residence. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Lisa is 17 year old South African national. She arrived with her mother on a visit visa when she was a small child. Her </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">mother overstays her visa and whilst in the UK she gives birth to Lisa’s younger sister </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Noeleen</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">. Lisa’s mother is an alcoholic and a drug addict. The Local Authority have concerns over the mother’s ability to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">care for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Noeleen</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">, who is 5 years old at the tim</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">e, and she is taken into Local Authority care. Lisa remains with her mother. Lisa’s mother dies due to her drug and alcohol problems. Following her mother’s death Lisa goes to the Local Authority to tell them what happens and ask for help. They fail to pro</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">vide her with support and accommodation and Lisa is homeless although a school friend has allowed her to sleep on her sofa for a few nights.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="71" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Many such children and young people only </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">realise</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> their precarious situation and seek legal advice, at pivotal deve</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">lopmental points in their life, such as when they apply to go to university or apply for a job. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Shalia</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> was a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">17 year old Zimbabwean </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">national who arrived into the UK with her family. The family were granted </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">leave to remain in the UK</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">. Due to abuse within t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">he family home </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Shaila</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> ran away. She was housed by the Local Authority. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Shaila</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> was later subjected to abuse by her support worker. She </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">had in fact</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> taken by her support worker to live with at her flat. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The Local Authority failed to support and accommodate he</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">r. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">It was later discovered that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Shaila</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> had no immigration status because her family had failed to apply for indefinite leave to remain on her behalf. Her refugee status had expired. Through specialist support her support worker was suspended and is under p</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">olice investigation. She was housed by the Local Authority and her immigration matters were resolved. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">              </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Abdul is a 17 year old Bangladeshi national whose mother has a history of mental health issues. He was in care from the age of 10 to 13 and then went </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">to live with his father until a year and half ago when he returned to his mother. Abdul’s mother assaulted and threatened Abdul with a knife and the police said it was not safe for him to return home. Abdul approached the Local Authority for assistance and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> was advised that he should sofa-surf until he went to university. With specialist support we challenged the local authority’s refusal to carry out a child in need assessment and provide Abdul with accommodation by way of a pre-action protocol letter. Abdu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">l was then provided with support and accommodation from Social Services. This sort of action against a public body whom is meant to have the best interests of a young person in mind, would not be possible without the help of free and independent specialist</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> lawyers.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="72" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Lack </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">of access to legal aid for imm</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">igration</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> matters </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">will cause a state of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">triple vulnerability </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">for undocumented migrant children and young people. They will remain</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> isolated, lone children with no access to advice for imm</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">igration</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> matters and in turn unable to access advice for public body failures and breaches </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">of their </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">duties and responsibilities. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="73" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The law in this area is not simple and asking children and young people to argue the applicability of international instruments, legi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">slation and policy to their own cases is plainly unreasonable. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Furthermore, it must be reiterated that this test affects access to all areas of civil law. Migrant children and young people, as noted above, are likely to have compound legal problems, relati</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ng to their status but also their accommodation, their education, their social support and possibly their employment entitlements. As such, while we would contend that it is unreasonable to expect a child or young person to represent themselves in an immig</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ration tribunal or to the Home Office’s immigration service, it is flagrantly absurd to suggest that such children should also develop sufficient expertise across all these legal disciplines. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="74" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Public authorities and the lower courts and tribunals in the U</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">K have increasingly benefited over the last several years from a swathe of public law decisions by the Administrative Court, Court of Appeal and UK Supreme Court concerning children and young people who otherwise would not meet the residence test. The deve</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">lopment of law in the area concerning children’s rights in relation to various public authorities exemplifies </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the fact that, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">sadly</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> authorities make the wrong decisions </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">frequently and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> require judicial assistance in the interpretation of their statutory dut</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This action, it shouldn’t need to be reiterated, is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a legitimate</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and key function of the courts, which underpins the UK constitution. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="75" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Many of our young clients have spent the majority of their lives in UK education from primary to secondary age, and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> consider themselves like their school friends to be British, in ignorance of their circumstances. It cannot be denied that these children and young people have significant ties to the UK</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> The government may wish to assert that the remedy in such compellin</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">g cases is simple and accessible without legal aid, but this is not the case. We have had to mount many challenges against decisions of the Home Office, which seek to assert the prominence of immigration control over the alleged wrong- doings and immigrati</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">on offences of children. UK law in this area is clear; any child implicated in conduct by the state must have their best interests considered as a primary consideration (ZH Tanzania) and on a case-specific basis (SM &amp; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Anor</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">). This means that the circumstanc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">es of individual children must be assessed in the round, and are not amenable to broad-based policies that assume certain outcomes for the children concerned. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="76" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Children and young people’s cases are not simple, and the residence test will obstruct this you</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ng group of clients from accessing legal representation. Similarly, our housing and education teams have been compelled to bring challenges for young people and their families who would fail the residence test and otherwise be unable to have a voice in our</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> community, and challenge the decisions of local authorities. The tool of legal aid is incredibly important to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ensure that the voices, welfare, best interests and legitimate legal concerns of young people and their families in our community are heard.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="77" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Mor</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e specifically, we are also gravely concerned that the failure to provide irregular migrant children with legal aid will mean that they are denied local authority accommodation pending their immigration status being investigated and resolved, to which they</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> are entitled under the Children Act 1989. As noted above with regard to asylum seekers, the imposition of destitution on adults in these circumstances would certainly breach the threshold of Article 3 ECHR. In the case of children such circumstances would</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> obviously constitute an even more egregious violation.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="78" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">It is impossible for us to see how such assessments can be conducted without the interests of a child being represented by trained and experienced </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">lawyers.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> In general, then, the failure to provide legal aid to children is liable to be ruled in breach of the UK’s duties under the UNCRC in conjunction with Article 8 of the ECHR. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">v</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">              </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">The impact of the Residence test on the Law</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="79" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The following is a list of very</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> important cases that had immense importance to individual clients as well as to public bodies and have had significant impact in developing and clarifying the law across the UK. If the residence test had been in force at the time it is very likely these c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ases could not have been brought:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">R (KA) v Essex [2013] EWHC 43 (Admin) – a Nigerian family with three children born in the UK, the eldest aged 8. The family who had their Article 8 immigration application refused without a right of appeal. They challenge</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">d the decision that would result in their support being withdrawn by the local authority, and had requested removal directions be issued, so they could appeal against them on the basis of Article 8. This was an effective safeguard of their Article 8 rights</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and so constituted a legal barrier to return and thus the local authority should continue to support.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ZH (Tanzania) v Secretary of State for the Home Department [2011] UKSC 4 – British national children with non-British mother at risk of removal; human r</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ights assessments should take account of the best interests and wishes of the child and take account of the fact that a child is British, born here and has developed a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">private life in the UK. The best interests of a child were held to be a primary consider</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ation.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">R (VC) v Newcastle [2011] EWHC 2673 (Admin) – refused asylum seeker with two children born in the UK should be eligible for support under s 17 CA rather than s 4 Home Office support, since s 4 is a residual power. The local authority could only tre</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">at s 4 support as otherwise available if they could show the Home Office were willing or could be compelled to provide this support.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">R (SO) v London Borough of Barking &amp; Dagenham [2010] EWCA </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Civ</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> – local authorities do have the power and can have a duty to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> accommodate care leavers in order to safeguard their wellbeing and human rights.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Birmingham City Council v Clue [2010] EWCA </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Civ</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> 460 – human rights assessments following a child in need assessment under s 17 CA should treat an outstanding Article 8 immigr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ation application as a barrier to return and also consider a child/family’s private life as separate from family life.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">R (M) v Slough [2008] UKHL 52 – a ‘need for care and attention not otherwise available’ under s 21 NAA means a need for looking after, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">support with something a person cannot reasonably be expected to do for themselves.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">PB v </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Haringey</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> [2006] EWHC 2255 (Admin) – Jamaican </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">overstayer</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> with 5 (non-resident) children in the UK applied for accommodation under s 21 NAA; the Court found her mental </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">health problems had not been properly considered and her Article 8 ECHR right to family life.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">R (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Limbuela</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">) v SSHD [2005] UKHL 66 – a refusal of support a person would be eligible for but for their immigration status can breach Article 3 ECHR by amounting </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to inhuman and degrading treatment.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">M v Islington [2004] EWCA </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Civ</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> 235 – before a local authority can limit their support to an offer of tickets to return they need to assess whether the child would be a child in need on return, whether requiring return wo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">uld breach the family’s human rights and whether requiring a British citizen child to leave the UK would breach their human rights. Case brought by </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Guyanan</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> mother with British child.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 3.8pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">E. The proposal that judicial reviews against public bodies should only b</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">e paid for if the Court grants permission for the application to proceed</span></p><ol start="80" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Judicial Review is a vital safeguard against the unlawful acts and omissions of public bodies and is a fundamental component of the rule of law. We believe that it is draconian and pe</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">rverse to propose steps that would dent the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">constitutional right of equality of arms for members of the public, particularly vulnerable groups such as children and young people and those at the mercy of public body decision-making. Access to judicial revie</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">w is of significant constitutional importance and to seek to obstruct, limit or restrict a person’s constitutional right should be very carefully considered by the coalition government.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="81" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In our view, the fact that so many judicial review claims are brought</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> is a reflection upon the poor quality decision making of public bodies, and not of vexatious lawyers or litigants</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. The heart of our judicial system is to ensure that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">there are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">checks and balances of public body decision-making</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> where fundamental human righ</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ts are in question</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="82" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">believe that the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> propositions put forward by</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the coalition government:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><ol type="a" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.78pt; padding-left:4.22pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Lack</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> insight into existing </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">measures and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">mechanisms </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">that exist in the current legal aid and judicial system, which already seek to limit unmeritorious claims</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">; </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 68.33pt; padding-left:3.67pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">F</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ail</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to accurately </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">evidence and/or quantify the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> justification for bring</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> in such a proposal</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 67.1pt; padding-left:4.9pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Fail to consider the impact that such measures </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">will have on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">day to day legal practice of suppliers; and</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 68.33pt; padding-left:3.67pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Fail to understand the importance of access to justice for</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">members of the public to pursue a legitimate claim for judicial review. </span></li></ol></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt; text-indent:-36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">i)</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">E</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">xisting measures and mechanisms that exist in the current legal aid and judicial system to limit </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">unmeritorious claims</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 54pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="83" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We believe that it is important to highlight to the Committee </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the various checks, measures and safeguards that exist in the current system to ensure that unmeritorious claims are not pursued by suppliers.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="84" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">On 1 April 2013 the newly formed L</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">egal </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">id </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">A</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">gency (LAA)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> removed the devolved powers of legal aid providers in judicial review </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">(JR) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">cases, this means that legal aid suppliers will </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">no longer be able to self-grant funding applications for judicial review cases. All legal aid suppliers now </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">have to apply to the LAA</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> for a publicly funded certificate and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ensure that a claimants’ case satisfies the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> merits and means tests. The LAA will decide the application according to the applicable regulations and guidance in place. Therefore</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> there </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">is already</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> a clear filter process</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> in place whereby the LAA can agree or disagree with a suppliers assertion there is merit to bri</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ng a judicial review claim. We submit that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> is the point at which it is reasonable to test the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">merits (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">likelihood of success</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">) of a claim</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, not whether or not the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">court grants permission</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, particularly as in our</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> experience, judicial review claims </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">commonly </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">settle pre- permission stage. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="85" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">As suppliers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> we must consider carefully the merits of bringing a claim from the outset and at the time we apply to the LAA for fund</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ing. In order to justify the merits of prospects of success we prepare detailed submissions to the LAA and often accompany the application with an advice from counsel on merits and prospects. We believe to render this process redundant makes a mockery of t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">he current checks and balances that exist through LAA decision-making. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="86" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The proposals cannot therefore</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, in our view,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> be justified on the basis </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">legal aid is being used to bring </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">‘</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">weak cases</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> before the court where such grants of legal aid have been </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">aut</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">horised</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">first </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">by the LAA. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We do not accept the Government’s contention that weak cases are commonly being brought and granted legal aid by the LAA. However, given that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the government</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> have decided to persist with this line</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> of argument</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">we believe that it is</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> only fair to query why the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">MoJ</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">has failed to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> consider and examine the practices of the LAA to establish why, in their view, funding is granted by the LAA for allegedly ‘weak cases’? Would it not be cost effective to assess the current filter mechanisms wi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">thin the LAA? Their decision-making, capacity and/or training needs?</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="87" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In our experience, many cases settle pre-permission because the Defendant (public body) has taken steps to settle the claim, withdrawn the decision subject to challenge. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We note the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">MoJ</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">has stated that they </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">believe</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> suppliers are misleading them </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">when notifying them of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the outcome of the case </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">whether there was a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> substantive benefit afforded to a client to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">pursue a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> claim</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, particularly in cases where the case did not proceed to permission</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">However, under the current regime the supplier</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s must</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> submit </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a final claim</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to the LAA for an assessment of costs</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, including information about the benefit of bringing the claim for the claimant</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. The claims are open for scrutiny and the LAA could simply make </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">its own assessment about substantive benefit to the client at this time in order to determine whether f</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">unding should ha</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ve been awarded, having the opportunity to carefully consider </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">why there was no longer a need to proceed with the case </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and/or </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to challenge</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> a refusal of permission.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="88" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Furthermore, the Committee should note that as suppliers we have a duty to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">he public purse not to wastefully incur costs and t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">here are further safeguards in place to ensure there isn’t an abuse of the court system by suppliers. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The Court has the power to order a Wasted Costs Order against either </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">party to the claim</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> if they consider there has been an act or omission that has resulted in costs being incurred which should not have been, including the bringing of a claim with no legit</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">imate legal challenge.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">ii</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">. Failure </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">of the Government </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">to accurately evidence and/or quantify their justification for bringing in such a proposal</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="89" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We have read the statistical data provided in the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">MoJ’s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Consultation paper and do not agree with the figures o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">r the analysis surrounding cost savings and the interpretation of those judicial review claims issued between 2011 and 2012. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="90" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The MOJ’s analysis does not concur with our substantive experience of acting for clients, including children and y</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">oung people, in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> judicial review cases</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We note that the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">MoJ’s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> proposal is justified in- part on the basis of a £1m costs saving, but there is insufficient breakdown of MOJ’s analysis and lack of evidence for this to be a credible statement. Even if it were the case </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">around £1m could be saved, we consider that this would be at the direct cost of access to justice for thousands of the most vulnerable in our communities, including lone children and young people and the proposal is completely disproportionate in terms of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the alleged monetary saving as against the huge impact on our rule of law.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="91" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Firstly, the proposal incorrectly assumes that the grant of permission by the court in a judicial review claim is the only indicator of success for the legally aided client. In actual fact, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">in our experience, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">once a claim is properly put through </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">pre- act</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ion correspondence and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> where required, the issuing of a judicial review claim, it is our experience that often the public authority Defendant can be compelled to settle the claim on the advice of their lawyers, whether that is the Treasury Solicitor’s dep</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">artment or in- house legal teams.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="92" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The proposal fails to understand key elements of our legal system, that judicial review is a remedy of last resort and that both parties have a duty to mediate and negotiate and attempt to settle the disput</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e outside of co</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">urt proceedings.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="93" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In some cases, particularly where the omission or action of the public body defendant will breach a claimants human rights, a claim may need to be lodged in order to compel the local Authority to act and/or not to act. In such cases an ap</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">plication for urgent interim relief is usually sought. This is particularly so in cases involving children and young people who are at risk of being homeless and destitute if the Local Authority fails to provide accommodation.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="94" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ILC’s housing team, and part</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">icularly our </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">StreetLegal</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> project for young people, deals with many such cases and it is a sad truth that local authorities do make unlawful housing decisions. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The ILC </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">StreetLegal</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> project has been running since 2004 and 70% of our cases with young people in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">volve breaches of law by local authorities, and the threat of judicial review challenges. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Many of the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> cases result in the respective local authority backing down with positive outcomes for our vulnerable client group. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Sarah is a 17 year old who was refer</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">red for psychiatric services when she was rescued by a passer-by from attempting to throw herself off a bridge. Sarah is the sole </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">carer</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> for her mother and younger siblings and has been finding it difficult to cope with her studies and responsibilities. Sar</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">ah’s mother refuses to engage with support services and Sarah’s psychiatrist has been trying to refer Sarah to the local authority for a child in need assessment under the Children Act 1989 but was not having any success in doing so. Sarah’s mother told he</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">r that she could not return to the house and Sarah was facing street homelessness. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Streetlegal</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> wrote a pre-action protocol letter challenging the local authority’s failure to carried out the assessment and provide Section 20 accommodation. Following this t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">he local authority accommodated Sarah whilst an assessment was being carried out by social services. The local authority then accepted a full Section 20 duty under the Children Act 1989 to accommodate and look after Sarah. Sarah would have been unable to v</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">entilate her case without the expert help of legal aid lawyers.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Amber is a 20 year old who has two children aged 1 and 2. Amber’s mother was diagnosed with cancer in January 2010 when she was pregnant with her second child. Amber’s mother asked her to lea</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">ve as there was not enough space in the house for her to stay. Amber approached the local authority to make a housing application and was told that she could only apply for private rented accommodation and was not entitled to temporary accommodation. The L</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">ocal Authority however did not offer any private accommodation and each time Amber called up she was told someone would call back but they never did. Amber’s mother passed away in November 2010 and has still not been provided with any accommodation. Amber’</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">s mother left her housing association to Amber’s older brother with whom Amber has always had a difficult relationship. Amber’s brother was </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">pressurising</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> her to leave and additionally there was an insect infestation in the house that he was refusing to addr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">ess. Amber’s doctor wrote a letter concerning Amber’s skin condition and the local authority had still not provided her with any accommodation. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Streetlegal</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> wrote a letter to the local authority proposing to commence judicial review proceedings if they did </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">not provide Amber with emergency temporary accommodation. Amber and her children were then provided with suitable accommodation. Amber was a particularly vulnerable young person who would have had little prospect of rectifying her situation without the ass</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">istance of a legal aid lawyer.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Mark was accommodated by the Local Authority under a Part VII homeless application under the Housing Act 1996 at 17 years old. When M turned 18 a Section 184 decision was made that he was not in priority need for accommodati</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">on. Mark was receiving psychiatric treatment and had been diagnosed with borderline personality disorder and had attempted suicide on two occasions while in temporary accommodation. When Mark received the letter saying he had been found not to be in priori</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">ty need for accommodation and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">cancelling his housing he attempted suicide and was </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">hospitalised</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Streetlegal</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> obtained a psychiatric report confirming that he would be vulnerable if he were street homeless as a result of his mental health issues and relied o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">n </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">caselaw</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> that it was unlawful for the Local Authority to have delayed the decision on his housing case until he turned 18. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Streetlegal</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> then requested a Section 202 review and made representations for interim accommodation with a threat of Judicial review </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">if the Local Authority did not provide it. The local authority provided interim accommodation and withdrew their Section 184 decision following full representation.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="95" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In some cases judicial review will be necessary to save breaches of an individual’s human </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">rights. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Tom was in his late 30’s when he approached ILC in a highly distressed state. He explained he was homeless having fled his secure accommodation due to homophobic violence. Tom was a former care leaver and had been subjected to severe sexual and e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">motional abuse during his time in care. Tom had been sectioned in the past and had a history of trying to take his own life. He applied to the local authority as a homeless person and was told verbally he was not vulnerable and temporary accommodation was </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">denied. In desperation he tried to commit suicide and was </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">hospitalised</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">. Upon his release from hospital Tom again approached the local authority homelessness department and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">he was told that he was </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">not vulnerable and therefore not in priority need. By the ti</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">me he reached ILC it was mid-afternoon and he was very distressed and informed us that he felt like killing himself. Urgent contact was made with the local authority and a request for urgent interim accommodation was made. Psychiatric evidence was provided</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> to the authority together with a request for the authority to review its decision under section 202 of the Housing Act 1996 (Part VII). The authority declined to provide interim accommodation pending the outcome of the review request. ILC had no option bu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">t to issue judicial review proceedings and seek urgent injunctive relief. That evening the High Court ordered the authority to provide interim accommodation. Whilst proceedings were issued the matter did not go to permission or a full trial as the local au</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">thority conceded their position, and Tom was spared the stress and trauma of lengthy litigation in the High Court. Tom was clearly very vulnerable and had the local authority fulfilled its statutory duty and made enquiries into his circumstances whilst pla</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">cing him in temporary accommodation, a judicial review would have been avoided.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="96" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In our experience, it is not uncommon for a claim to be lodged where </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">pre- action attempts </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">have failed but where the Defendant public body concedes the case pre-permission so the case </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">never goes before a judge</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Or in the alternative, a decision of the judge on the interim relief application settles unlawful action or omission. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">If there are clear grounds to demonstrate that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a public body</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> has acted unlawfully t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">hen it is not uncommon for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">senior lawyer</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s at a local authority or at </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Treasury solicitor</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, who may have only taken conduct of the matter after the judicial review claim was lo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">dged, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> advise the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">their public body client to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> withdraw the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ir</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> decision. This is common practice and is largely due to the structure and separation of local authority departments.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Shareen</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> is a 19 year old victim of sexual violence and was trafficked into </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">the UK for the purposes of sexual exploitation. She was supported by a trafficking charity who helped her make a claim for asylum. She is extremely traumatized and an urgent referral to a qualified psychiatrist has been made. There is a wealth of evidence </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">confirming her highly distressed state and concerns over her fitness for interview. Written submissions are made to the Home Office to request that her </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">asylum </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">interview be delayed pending the assessment of the psychiatrist. The Home Office refuse to postpo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">ne the interview. Professionals are extremely concerned that compelling </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Shareen</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> to attend an interview may damage her mental health and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">there is a risk that such an interview may </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">retrigger trauma. We write to the Home Office to advise that we will have no </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">choice but to lodge a claim for judicial review if they fail to reschedule the interview. If </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Shareen</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> does not attend her </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">interview, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">and the Home Office do not agree to rescheduling</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> her claim for asylum can be refused on non-compliance grounds.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">The Home Of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">fice refuse to engage with numerous pre-action correspondence and we have no choice but to lodge a claim </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">including</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> an urgent application for interim relief from the court. The judge considering the application orders that the interview be postponed pending</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> the outcome of the psychiatric assessment. Subsequently, we are contacted by Treasury Solicitors. We receive an apology for the lack of correspondence and advised that the decision to refuse our requests were made by a ‘new member of staff’ and the pre-ac</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">tion correspondence had not reached a senior official in time. The case is conceded and there is no need for the case to go up to a judge to consider whether permission be granted.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="97" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Frequently i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">t is not until a judicial review claim is lodged and a lawyer </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">looks at the papers that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the decision is reversed. A</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">nother example of this issue, within our own immigration teams, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">is that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">in the last 18 months, we have issued seven Judicial Review claims against the Home Office for failure to consider our client’s case</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s in accordance with its stated aims and policies under the Legacy </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Programme</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">; five of these </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">cases have been </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">conceded pre-permission</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> once the case has been considered by a lawyer for the Home Office</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="98" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Under the current proposals, and in all the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> scenario</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s above, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">we</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> would </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">not be paid by the LAA as the permission application was ne</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ver looked at by a judge and the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> remedy agreed directly with the Defendant.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="99" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In our view, i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">t is a very crude assertion therefore to test the merits of a Judicial Review claim in r</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">eliance on the statistics on grant of permission, given that so many settle pre-permission or that claims are withdrawn because of a new decision</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">I</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">n fact the premise of the Court Procedure Rules is to encourage parties to negotiate and settle.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="100" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">One may qu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ery why, if the case settled successfully</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the lawyers could not apply for their costs directly from the public body concerned. We do sometimes settle on the basis the other side agrees to pay our costs but often a quick remedy is agreed between the partie</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s to which the Defendant public body will agree on the basis that we do not seek costs</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> against them. In any event, this would </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">amount to little more than governmental cost shifting and it would in fact cost government more in the long- run, as the privately</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> paid rates lawyers can claim from the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">public body Defendant</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> significantly exceed the rates paid in legal aid cases. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">iii. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">The impact that this proposal will have on day to day practice and the long term effect on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">the public</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="101" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We submit that the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> proposal </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">is manifestly unfair and we consider that the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">MoJ</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> cannot reasonably expect legal aid suppliers to work at risk, for free, in cases where they are successfully challenging the decisions of public authorities and winning their clients’ legitimate cases becau</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">se the Defendant public body has accepted the unlawfulness of their failures, actions or omissions pre-permission.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="102" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Transferring all financial risk to legal aid suppliers will seriously impinge the rights of those eligible to legal aid from challenging unl</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">awful decisions by way of Judicial Review. Legal aid suppliers simply cannot bear the weight of such a significant risk and consequently, they will decline to take on the work and potential claimants will find it very difficult to access free legal advice.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Furthermore, many firms will simply decide that they are unable to continue in practice and we will see further legal practices close and the decline of quality legal service provision for members of society.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="103" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">MoJ</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> state that reasonable disbursements, such</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> as expert fees and court fees, which arise in preparing the permission application, would continue to be paid, even if permission was not granted by the court</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. However, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">there is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">complete disregard for the preparatory work required by a solicitor in prepar</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ing a claim for judicial review, particularly where the claimant is vulnerable and where significant issues around their liberty and/or health are at stake. The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">MoJ</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> proposes not to fund lawyers for this vital work under the new proposals. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="104" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">P</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">reparing an application for permission to apply for judicial review requires a substantial amount of work </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">that will have to be conducted at the financial risk of the firm or organization concerned</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, to name a view steps we must take in every day practice</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Obtaining documentary evidence relating to the issues in contention i.e. medical reports, statements from professionals etc </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Advising the client on the process and advising on next steps, outcome and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">settelment</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Settle the facts relied upon and the grounds </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">of review. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Completing application forms and appl</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ications for injunctive relief</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Preparing bundles of key </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">documents</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, subjective and objective evidence relied upon and a  legislative bundle </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 64.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Draft orders for the parties and the Court to agree on. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="105" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Clearly, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the wor</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">k required is very significant and we are bemused why the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">MoJ</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> believes that such work is not necessary and/or can be paid at risk. We believe that if such a measure is brought in there will be a host of suppliers who will not take a gamble with the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">firms / organizations suitability and therefore this will have a major impact on the lives of many vulnerable people, where there health, safety and liberty are at serious risk as highlighted in the examples above.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="106" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Furthermore, we believe that the propo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">sal would in effect ensure only that the poor cannot hold the government to account.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="107" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We would also argue that the result of judicial review work can also be hugely significant in benefitting the wider community, far beyond the particular interests of an i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ndividual claimant</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and if such cases are not pursue this will have a substantial impact on UK society as a whole</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. The following seminal cases exemplify the individual, governmen</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">tal and guiding benefits of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Administrative Court and onward appellate court</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s in the areas of the law that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">MiCLU</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> works in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">k, and which may not have been possible if a firm / </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">organisation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> suspected that their work would be at risk</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">R (G) v </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Southwark</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> LBC [2009] 1 WLR 1299- Baroness Hale held that although it may be appropriate in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">some circumstances for children in need to be accommodated where they don’t need support pursuant to section 17 of the Children’s Act, and in so doing the children’s authority could seek to avail </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">themselves of the services of other departments and services</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> such as the housing authority’s homelessness scheme, this did not replace the statutory duty of care to the child and the children’s authority could not “pass the buck” to another authority.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">R (A) v Croydon London Borough Council [2009] UKSC 8- The Supre</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">me Court handed down a key judgment in joined cases R (on the application of A) (FC) (Appellant) v London Borough of Croydon (Respondents)and R (on the application of M) (FC) (Appellant) v London Borough of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Lambeth</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (Respondents) concerning the question of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">who is the ultimate arbiter of whether or not an individual is a “child” such that they might be determined to be a “child in need” under the Children Act 1989 (the “Act”). These two cases had been joined with five other claims for judicial review, of whic</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">h the two named were treated as the lead cases.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">R (Singh) v </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Aberdare</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Girls School [2008]EWHC 1865 (Admin) [2008] ELR 561 - A school's decision to refuse to allow a Sikh pupil to wear a Kara bangle at school constituted indirect discrimination on grounds </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">of race under the Race Relations Act 1976 and on the grounds of religion under the Equality Act 2006. When S was told that she could not attend school unless she stopped wearing the Kara, that constituted an exclusion with the consequence that S could invo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ke the appropriate appeal procedure. The school failed to take into account the relevant guidance when excluding S.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Vu v </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Lewisham</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Borough Council and the Special Educational Needs Tribunal (2000) unreported - the High Court held that the tribunal was wron</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">g to determine that the mother's (not the child in question) need for interpretation from Vietnamese to English was not an educational need for the child so as to require that it be set out in Part 3 (special educational provision required) of the child's </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">statement. The basis for this decision was that it was an acknowledged need of the child that there be very close home-school liaison so that where, in this case, the mother's need for interpretation to facilitate this was required, it would be provision e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ffectively required by the child.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">F. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The proposal that legal aid should be removed for all cases assessed as having “borderline” prospects of success</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="108" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We believe that the proposals undermine the efficiency of the current legal aid system and practice of t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">he Legal Aid Agency (LAA) and the UK court system.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="109" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">As mentioned above, w</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e are bemused as to the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">MoJ</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">’s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> failure to properly acknowledge the current structure within the current legal aid system with existing filters in place whereby the LAA can agree or dis</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">agree with a legal aid suppliers assertion there is merit to bring a judicial review claim in cases with borderline prospects of success. These cases are not automatically funded under the legal aid regime and thus the abolition of the category is unwarran</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ted and unnecessary. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="110" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Under the current system a legal aid supplier will need to complete an application for funding in all cases requiring a funding certificate. As part of this application process a supplier must explain, in the Statement of Case sectio</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">n of the application, why the case is borderline and justify why funding should be granted. The LAA will assess the application and can refuse such an application if it does not agree with the assessment of the merits by the legal aid supplier. In our expe</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">rience, if an application is refused then usually a request for a review of that decision will be made and considered on the papers. We have a number of solicitors within </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">MiCLU</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and the ILC who have a considerable amount of experience in making applications</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to the LAA and it is our experience that it is very rare for a case to go to a hearing before the Independent Funding Adjudicator (IFA). With a combined experience of 70 years of legal practice we know of only 1 case that has been placed before the IFA. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="111" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">MoJ</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> consultation has failed to provide evidence or statistical data on the number of applications made by a legal aid supplier under the borderline test and of these applications how many have been refused, granted and/or then proceeded to a IFA heari</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ng and the outcome of such appeals. We assert that without this important data it is difficult to see why the current system is not sufficient and why such a process may be considered ‘costly’ if that is indeed inferred by the need for the abolition of suc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">h a test. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="112" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Cases funded where there are borderline prospects of success are very particular types of cases where</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> frequently, a novel </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">important point of law has been identified, and the guidance of the courts is required or there are compelling human </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">rights considerations. The proposals fail to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">recognise</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> that often, cases and appeals are adjudged as borderline through the lower courts, High Court and even Court of Appeal stages because they are pushing a new point of law or relate to cases involving a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">significant wider public interest e.g. concern legislative interpretation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This process of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> testing points of law</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> surrounding children’s rights</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> for example, can often result</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the Appellant </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">only finally succeeding </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">before the UK Supreme Court as it is best</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> placed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> as the most senior domestic court</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to provide a conclusive and new ruling. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="113" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In our experience many cases involving the consideration of children’s rights are likely to involve complex legal issues and often have a significant wider </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">public interes</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">t, particularly where there are new statutory provisions, policy and guidance pertaining specifically to the rights of children and which require judicial oversight, interpretation and scrutiny. It is vital that cases assessing and testing legal principles</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and legislative interpretation of such rights are awarded legal aid funding. Through proper judicial scrutiny the law can evolve to meet the needs and demands of a changing society, the evolution of children’s rights and ensure that the UK Government meet</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s its obligations under domestic and international law. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="114" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Assessing a case’s success rate is not an accurate science. This proposal will exclude a large number of potentially successful cases and will be extremely detrimental to many people who will be obs</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">tructed from access to justice because they cannot afford to fund their cases privately. Again this change will make the justice system a privilege for the rich rather than a public service.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="115" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Finally, and with particular reference to the rights of separate</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">d children seeking international protection in the UK, in June 2005 the [then] LSC issued a concessionary policy paper to the extent that all children’s cases would be guaranteed access to Controlled Legal Representation for asylum appeals, irrespective of</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">individualised</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> merit</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and if the case was at least borderline</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. This was a move that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">recognised</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> protection principles for children in adversarial systems, and allowed them access to legal aid in appeals advancing international protection grounds, paying particular attention to the additional vulnerabilities of childr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">en and the need for child-specific considerations in their claims. We understand that the concession, issued in “LSC Immigration Services Team Newsletter” of 20 June 2005 (Issue 24) formed part of the borderline principle provisions. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We annex a copy of tha</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">t letter to our evidence. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="116" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">It is unclear whether the proposal to remove borderline cases out of scope would also remove appeal representation for such cases. We strongly submit that the given right to representation should continue, and the 2005 concessio</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">n rightly a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ffirms current law and practice</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">To </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">have a blanket ban on ‘borderline’ cases may well prejudice the rights of refugee children and their ability to access justice. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">G</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">The proposed restriction on the scope of legal aid available to prisoners</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="117" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">MiCLU</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and ILC do not have a prison law contract but we do refer detained clients for specialist prison law advice, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">who ate </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">some of the most vulnerable clients we work with. We are deeply concerned that the changes will mean that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">all</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> treatment cases will fa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ll out of legal aid scope, whether they relate to adults and/or children and young people. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="118" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The proposals would do away with legal aid for treatment cases, including matters concerning:</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Prison conditions (food, correspondence, access to education and reh</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">abilitation facilities, culturally/ religious sensitive treatment and facilities), </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Treatment by staff (bullying, abuse), </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Discrimination, </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Communications and visits, </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Mother and baby issues, </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Compassionate release, </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Access to behavior courses and access </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to medical care.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="119" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The proposals also intend to cut legal aid for all disciplinary matters, unless they are referred to an independent adjudicator and certain sentencing matters, (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">categorisation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, segregation, close supervision centre and dangerous and seve</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">re personality disorder referrals and assessments, resettlement issues, and planning and license conditions). These are incredibly important matters concerning fundamental civil rights and without access to a specialist lawyer most prisoners, including </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">chi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ldren, young people and the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">particularly vulnerable, will be unable to fully advance claims, complaints and issues.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="120" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Prisoners are amongst the most vulnerable in our communities and wholly reliant upon the State. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Institutionalisation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, loss of liberty, the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">strong demands for compliance in the prison system, danger from other prisoners, and social stigma all contribute to causing vulnerability amongst incarcerated people. Inherent vulnerability caused by the prison system is often exacerbated by particular me</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ntal and physical health problems, learning disabilities, language and literacy issues, and substance abuse. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="121" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The following statistics and information are noteworthy:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">More than 70% of the prison population has two or more mental health disorders</span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Male p</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">risoners are 14 times more likely to have two or more disorders than men in general, and female prisoners are 35 times more likely than women in general </span><a name="_ftnref12"></a><a href="#_ftn12">[12]</a></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The suicide rate in prisons is almost 15 times higher than in the general population: in 2002 the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">rate was 143 per 100,000 compared to 9 per 100,000 in the general population</span><a name="_ftnref13"></a><a href="#_ftn13">[13]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Whereas around 8% of the general population scores within the learning disabled or borderline group, this increases to 32% for people detained in prisons as of research publishe</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">d in 2007</span><a name="_ftnref14"></a><a href="#_ftn14">[14]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 28.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In the UK, around 80% of prisoners have literacy problems ranging from illiteracy to reading and writing problems</span><a name="_ftnref15"></a><a href="#_ftn15">[15]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="122" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In addition, criminality can and does arise from being trafficked to the UK, or from other forms of ill- treatment and exploi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">tation. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">MiCLU</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and ILC have previously provided specialist immigration legal advice to children in Young Offenders Institutes and women prisoners at HMP Holloway. It was abundantly clear </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">from our work </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">that many of these </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">children and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">women had significant me</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ntal health problems, were victims of trafficking and care leavers who had been subjected to abus</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e, ill-treatment and/or neglect and yet </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">w</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e note with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">dismay that there are no exceptions for children, and those prisoners who are accepted to have mental health problems, a disability or other vulnerability, including those who may not have legal capacity. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="123" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Children and young people in detention are some o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">f the most vulnerable in society. Not only because of their minority but also because of their detention, isolation and separation from family. In our experience many young detainees have additional vulnerabilities such </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">as </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">mental illness and cognitive impa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">irment, past experience of abuse and neglect and many who have been in the care system prior to entering into detention. The level of support needs and access to services varies considerably with many complex cases involving a multitude of issues that requ</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ire specialist support. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">M</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">ohammed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> is a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">16 year old</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> who was in the care of a Local Authority. He was abused and exploited as a street child in Libya and later in Greece, having arrived into the UK to seek safety. Due to his past traumatic experiences he be</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">came depressed, addicted to solvents and later heroin. As a result, he was convicted for petty offences. During his time in Young Offenders Institute (YOI) he was not provided adequate support services or access to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">behaviour</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> management courses</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">. He was </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">plac</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">ed in segregation for lengthy periods of time all of which had a direct impact on his rehabilitation. He was also denied access to contact with his mother. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">A</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">dam</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> is a 17 year old </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">national from Senegal</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">severe </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">mental health problems. He has indefinite </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">leave to remain in the UK and his family are British Citizens. He was charged and sentenced for offences relating to his gang affiliation in a local </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">housing estate in North London.  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Unfortunately, there has been a breakdown in the family relationship and t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">he Home Office have decided to take deport action to remove him from the UK. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Upon release he was denied support from the Local Authority. He was later assessed as having significant cognitive impairments with an assessed mental capacity of a 5 year old. Sp</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">ecialist legal advice was needed to ensure that the Local Authority fulfilled their statutory duties to provide adequate accommodation, support services and protection from gang reprisals.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Belinda is 16 year old from the DRC. Her family were killed duri</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">ng the civil conflict whereby significant human rights abuses were committed against women and children. Belinda is orphaned at the age of 12 and has been raped on numerous occasions. She is later trafficked for the purposes of sexual exploitation through </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">several African countries. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">During this time she falls pregnant and is subjected to a forced abortion. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">Her traffickers </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">later </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">facilitate her entry to the UK through a false visa placing her age beyond her actual minority. She is internally trafficked through</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic"> England and is imprisoned in a brothel for several years. Belinda was finally able to escape her trafficking situation and was street homeless in a major UK city before she was helped by a female stranger. When she arrived at the police station she was pl</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">aced into the care of the Local Authority and housed in a foster placement because of her vulnerabilities. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">She is taken to the Home Office by her social worker. At no stage have the police or the Local Authority disputed Belinda’s minority, she was 16 at t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">he time. Having arrived at the Home Office the immigration official note that she is trafficked victim having listened to Belinda’s account and that of her social worker. Whilst at the Home Office Belinda is abandoned by her social worker. She has no idea </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">where she has gone and is forced to wait at the Home Office alone before she is told to travel with a man and boy in a car. Belinda does not know where she is being taken and is extremely scared. Upon leaving the car she is met by a housing officer who inf</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">orms her that she will be staying at the accommodation before she is taken back to the Home Office. A week later Belinda is taken to the Home Office and told that her age is being disputed. The Home Office rely on the visa application that was used to faci</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">litate her entry to the UK. She is taken to adult accommodation for asylum seekers. She is alone and isolated for several weeks before the accommodation she lives in is raided by immigration officers. She is arrested and taken to HMP Holloway having been c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">harged with immigration offences for making a false claim for asylum and entering the UK unlawfully. Whilst in prison concerns about her mental health and minority are raised by prison staff and immigration officers but no steps are taken to assess her nee</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">ds and provide her with appropriate support. Once the case was referred to use we secured he release from prison, she was age assessed by a Local Authority who later found her to be a child and she was placed in a foster placement once again. </span></p><ol start="124" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Children and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> young people who are unidentified victims of trafficking within the prison system would also be affected by the proposals and the proposals would in our view make </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">there</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> identification as victims less likely</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="125" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">R</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">esearch conducted in 2012 reports as follows:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> “The research, conducted last year, involved interviewing 103 of the over 600 foreign national women incarcerated in the UK at that time. Foreign nationals account for roughly one in seven of the total female prison population. The offences of 58 intervie</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">wees were linked directly to their victim status. Researchers identified 43 women as victims of human trafficking. Five more who entered the country freely had since worked in slave-like conditions.</span><a name="_ftnref16"></a><a href="#_ftn16">[16]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> ”</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="126" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Under the new proposals the three children above would have no access to specialist legal advice to ensure that they had contact with their family whilst in custody, adequate support services whilst detained, assistance with resettlement and rehabilitation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> upon release and/or no specialist support to identify complex trafficking needs. In the case of a young female with a baby, the young person would be unable to challenge a decision to separate her from her child by not placing them in a mother and baby un</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">it.  </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="127" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Instead, under the new proposals a detained child who may be unable to identify legal issues and will not have the financial resources to pay for lawyers, will be expected to navigate an adversarial system from within a Young Offenders’ Institute. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">As was recently highlighted in the Serious Case Review into the death of Alex Kelly in HMYOI </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Cookham</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Wood, children with complex needs and histories of abuse and/or neglect are unlikely to seek help and support .</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="128" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Such a child or person of any age with a m</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ental health problem or other relevant disadvantage may be unable to identify that something is wrong with the way they are being treated, but they will also have no means by which to fully frame complaints to the prison authority. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="129" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We note from the respo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">nse to the consultation the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">MoJ</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> has highlighted the role of advocacy services to assist children and young people with the various complaints mechanisms. However, we believe that such measures are wholly inadequate to ensure that the best interests of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">child are properly considered, their family rights are protected (under Article 8 European Convention on Human Rights) and/or their rights to ensure that their welfare is safeguarded and they are protected from inhuman or degrading treatment or punishment </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">(Article 3 European Convention on Human Rights). To ensure that their legal rights are protected and/or not breached it is crucial that they have </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">access to an independent judicial process with the assistance of a qualified legal representative.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="130" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">At ILC we </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">act for foreign national prisoners in immigration matters, and it is a fair statement to say that the above issues are represented amongst the majority of our detained clients. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="131" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We are alarmed that if the proposals come into effect we will no longer be ab</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">le to refer vulnerable detained clients for specialist help with treatment matters. Who will help an illiterate, elderly non- English speaking prisoner with a complaint against the prison, (which has a duty of care to him), to set out that his faith- based</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> food requirements are not being met, and he is being denied access to his family? Who will help a 17 year old age- disputed former street child from Morocco, who has a history of sexual abuse and exploitation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> with accessing educational and rehabilitation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> facilities? These examples represent true case studies. It is a sad fact that many foreign national prisoners are discriminated against and refused their rights and entitlements whilst in detention on the basis that the prison, often wrongly</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> assumes they</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> will be “deported” on completion of their sentence.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="132" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The consultation paper states that ‘the internal prisoner complaints system, prisoner discipline procedures and probation complaints system should be the first port of call’ for the cases from which it </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">proposes to remove legal aid</span><a name="_ftnref17"></a><a href="#_ftn17">[17]</a></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="133" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">However, we note that the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> Howard League for Penal Reform </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">has recently </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">reveal</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> that the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">MoJ</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> has conceded children held in secure training </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">centres</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (STCs) should have a right to an independent review of their complaints, in res</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ponse to a legal challenge by the charity. In a letter to the Howard League</span><a name="_ftnref18"></a><a href="#_ftn18">[18]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, the government’s solicitors confirmed that the jurisdiction of the Prisons and Probations Ombudsman will be extended to cover STCs with immediate effect. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Such a development was o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">nly secured as a result of legal action taken by independent solicitors, unconnected to the prisoner complaints system internal to prisons and YOIs. This example demonstrates that the complaints procedures in prisons and YOIs are clearly in need of substan</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">tial monitoring and, if necessary, firm legal action to correct mistakes that are made.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">H. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Conclusion </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="134" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">MiCLU</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and ILC </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">oppose</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Mo</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">J’s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> proposal for all the above reasons</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and believe that all the proposals discussed above should be abandoned in their entirety</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. They </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">are unworkable</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, unsubstantiated in terms of financial benefit, unequal and discriminatory, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">damaging to human rights </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and will seriously impinge access to justice</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and the rule of law.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> It is clear that the consequences of the proposals have not been thought through adequately </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">by the coalition </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">government </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and the assertion that such measure</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> are necessary to save public expenditure </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and money to the tax payer are, we s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ubmit, ill-founded and</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> u</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">nsubstantiated and at worst </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">woefully</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> misleading. </span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="135" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Legal aid is not a finan</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">cial benefit - </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">it is in place to ensure that those who cannot afford to pay for legal representation are afforded equal access to justice.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> We submit that the</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> proposal is not a proportionate response to the £1 million in public money the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">MoJ</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> claims it will save. In terms of government budgets the claimed saving would be paltry, whereas the effect on everyday people in the UK and their fundamental right to seek </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">redress for the wrongs of public bodies would be chillingly eroded.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="136" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">It is our position that access to legally aided advice in the areas above would obviate the foreseeable burdens upon the State and the courts. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Denying legally aided specialist advice would </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">not only </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ca</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">u</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">se detriment to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the most vulnerable </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">but </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">it will also create a detriment to the resources of many central and local government departments, including the Prison Service, the Home Office and Local Aut</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">horities </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and burden the Court</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s and Tribunals</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. A good legal aid lawyer would not advance </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a legal case</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> without legal merit, and certainly would not litigate on the back of any refusal in an unmeritorious claim</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Whereas, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">litigants in person with no legal expe</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">rtise will be unable to assess the chance of success in their own case, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">in some cases pursuing cases alone, which will increase the number of litigants in person desperate to access the rule of law in the UK.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="137" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; list-style-position:inside; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-indent:-18pt"><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">We are concerned that the removal of legal aid in these circumstances will lead to the loss of a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">legitimate legal </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">remedy in serious cases where children’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">rights are impinged</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">; the loss of important precedents to guide the future actions of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">public bodies, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">i</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">n circumstances where the relationship of domestic (often secondary) legislation with children’s rights can be unclear; and the risk that standards will decline as </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">public bodies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> become immune from judicial challenge.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 12pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">42</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:'Lucida Sans'; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">P</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">aragraph 3.1 of the Consultation; Impact Assessment MoJ194 paragraph 4</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Ibid paragraph 3.42 </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">   House of Commons Debate, ‘Transforming Legal Aid’, 5 Sep 2013 Column 499</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn4"></a><a href="#_ftnref4">[4]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Law Society Gazette, ‘SRA Survey Exposes 1200 Firms in Financial Difficulty’, </span><a href="http://www.lawgazette.co.uk/practice/sra-survey-exposes-1200-firms-in-financial-difficulty/5037705.article"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.lawgazette.co.uk/practice/sra-survey-exposes-1</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">200-firms-in-financial-difficulty/5037705.article</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn5"></a><a href="#_ftnref5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://detentionaction.org.uk/wordpress/wp-content/uploads/2013/06/Nick-Armstrong-Costing-the-civil-legal-aid-proposals-130624.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://detentionaction.org.uk/wordpress/wp-content/upload</span><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">s/2013/06/Nick-Armstrong-Costing-the-civil-legal-aid-proposals-130624.pdf</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn6"></a><a href="#_ftnref6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">Transforming Legal Aid: Next Steps, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">para</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> 2.12</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn7"></a><a href="#_ftnref7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Impact Assessment MoJ194 states at paragraph 21: ‘the LAA do not currently record the residency status of a client and therefore </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">the data is not available to estimate the impact on the value or volume of</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">cases this policy affects’</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn8"></a><a href="#_ftnref8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><a href="http://www.migrationobservatory.ox.ac.uk/sites/files/migobs/Briefing%20-%20Migration%20to%20the%20UK%20-%20Asylum.pdf"><span style="color:#0000ff; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.migrationobservatory.ox.ac.uk/sites/files/migobs/Briefing%20-%20Migration%20to%20the%20UK%20-%20Asylum.pdf</span></a></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn9"></a><a href="#_ftnref9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt">paragraph 3.74</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> of the consultation </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn10"></a><a href="#_ftnref10">[10]</a><span style="background-color:#ffff00; font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">The legacy programme was the name given to the then UKBA’s attempts to resolve the enormous </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">backlog of cases that had been built up from the mid 2000s onwards. It was scheduled to conclude in mid-2011 but large numbers of cases remain outstanding. The legacy department has since been renamed several times.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn11"></a><a href="#_ftnref11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">Social Exclusion Unit, 2004, quoting P</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">sychiatric Morbidity Among Prisoners In England And Wales, 1998</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn12"></a><a href="#_ftnref12">[12]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Social Exclusion Unit, 2004, quoting Psychiatric Morbidity Among Prisoners In England And Wales, 1998</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn13"></a><a href="#_ftnref13">[13]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> The National Service Framework For Mental Health: Five Years On, Department of Health,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> 2004; Samaritans Information Resource Pack, 2004</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn14"></a><a href="#_ftnref14">[14]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Prison reform Trust, “No-one Knows”, 2007- funded by the Diana Princess of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">wales</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Memorial Fund</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn15"></a><a href="#_ftnref15">[15]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> World Literacy Foundation, The Guardian 3 May 2010</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn16"></a><a href="#_ftnref16">[16]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> The University of Cambridge, Women trafficked into crime in UK are imprisoned without support or protection, 15 February 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn17"></a><a href="#_ftnref17">[17]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> Paragraph 3.15 of the consultation; </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn18"></a><a href="#_ftnref18">[18]</a><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> 6</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:6.67pt; vertical-align:super">th</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt"> September 2013 </span><a href="http://www.howardleague.org/stcvictory/"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">http://www.howar</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; text-decoration:underline">dleague.org/stcvictory/</span></a></p></body></html>